\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this letter, we extend our previous work on the foundations of computability
 in quantum mechanics by exploring the application of interval-valued probabilit
y measures (IVPM) to achieving a coherent formulation of finite-resource
 quantum mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are long-standing debates in the foundations of quantum mechanics
 regarding the tension between finite precision measurement and contextuality
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Peres2003,BarrettKent2004"

\end_inset

.
 For example, Meyer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.83.3751"

\end_inset

 and Mermin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mermin1999"

\end_inset

 disagree on whether finite-precision measurements invalidate the Kochen-Specker
 theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochenspecker1967,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

, and discussion continues on whether contextuality is experimentally verifiable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Spekkens2005,GuehneKleinmannCabelloEtAl2010,MazurekPuseyKunjwalEtAl2016"

\end_inset

.
 The fundamental question is how to make mathematical theories of quantum
 mechanics that are intrinsically, rather than only implicitly, consistent
 with the resources available for the realistic accuracy of an actual measuremen
t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our first observation is that essential objectives of our program to achieve
 a computable theory of quantum mechanics and finite-resource measurement,
 attempted previously with computable number systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "usat,geometry2013apsrev4,DQT2014"

\end_inset

, may be achievable by extending classical interval-valued probability measures
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JamisonLodwick2004"

\end_inset

 to the quantum domain.
 We begin by axiomatizing a quantum interval-valued probability measure
 (QIVPM) framework exploiting the fact that a density matrix approach can
 be considered as equivalent to a description of quantum states using probabilit
y measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "10.2307/2308516,Varadarajan2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Mackey=10.2307
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

One result is that the expectation value of an observable with respect to
 a QIVPM can be defined to be consistent with the constraints on the expectation
 value of the same observable expected from continuous quantum mechanics.
 We then examine Gleason's theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

 and the Kochen-Specker theorem in the context of QIVPM's, and conclude
 that they correspond to the limit of an infinite number of precise intervals,
 and the set of crypto-deterministic intervals (the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\imposs,\necess\}$
\end_inset

), respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note, however, that in this approach there exist QIVPM's that do not
 correspond to a density matrix computable by the Born rule, so that Gleason's
 theorem cannot hold in general.
 It thus remains possible that a refinement of the basic definition of a
 quantum state or the computation of probability from a state may be required
 when we rigorously consider the implications of finite precision measurement.
\end_layout

