\begin_layout Section
Fuzzy Measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
probability space
\emph default
 is a mathematical abstraction specifying the necessary conditions for reasoning
 coherently about collections of uncertain events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kolmogorov1950"

\end_inset

.
 In the quantum case, the events of interest are the 
\emph on
projection operators
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 This set includes the empty projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{0}$
\end_inset

, the identity projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}$
\end_inset

, projections of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{\psi}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is a pure quantum state, sums of 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 projections, and products of 
\emph on
commuting
\emph default
 projections.
 In a well-defined quantum probability space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "10.2307/2308516,gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,Maassen2010"

\end_inset

, each event 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is associated with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(P_{i})$
\end_inset

 subject to the following axioms: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\mathbb{0})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\mathbb{1})=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\mathbb{1}-P\right)=1-\mu\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

, and for a set of mutually orthogonal projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{i}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\mu\left(P_{i}\right)\textrm{ .}\label{eq:QuantumProbability-Addition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, consider a three-dimensional Hilbert space with orthonormal
 basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ket{0},\ket{1},\ket{2}\}$
\end_inset

 and an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 with spectral decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}+2\,\proj{1}+3\,\proj{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Here are two fragments of valid probability measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

 that can associated with this space: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(\proj{0})=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(\proj{1})=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(\proj{2})=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}(\proj{0})=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}(\proj{1})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}(\proj{2})=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 By the Born rule, the first probability measure corresponds to the quantum
 system being in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ket{0}+\alpha\ket{1})/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and the second corresponds to the quantum system being in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ket{0}+\alpha\ket{2})/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha|=1$
\end_inset

.
 The expectation value of the observable in the first case is 1.5 and in
 the second it is 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above axioms describe a mathematical idealization involving infinitely
 precise measurements.
 In an actual experimental setup with an ensemble of quantum states that
 are not exactly identical, and with small imperfections and inaccuracies
 in measuring devices, an experimenter might only be able to determine that
 the probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

 is in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.49,0.51]$
\end_inset

.
 The spread in this range depends on the amount of resources (time, energy,
 money, etc) that are devoted to the experiment.
 In the classical setting, this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzziness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is formalized by moving to 
\emph on
interval-valued probability measures
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To adapt the axioms of such IVPMs to the quantum case, we proceed as follows.
 First we fix a collection of intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 that represents an abstraction of the available experimental resources.
 At one extreme, infinitely precise resources would correspond to the collection
 of intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\{[x,x]\mid x\in[0,1]\}$
\end_inset

.
 This case should coincide with the idealized situation above.
 At another extreme, an experiment with 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 resources would correspond to the following three intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\unknown=[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 As before, the first two intervals are associated with the empty projection
 and the identity projection but every other projection would be associated
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\unknown$
\end_inset

; its probability can be anything in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 A third special situation would be to consider IVPMs with only the two
 intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This is what Peres calls the 
\emph on
crypto-deterministic
\emph default
 case in which there is no ambiguity about the status of any event; we know
 for certain if it will occur or not.
\end_layout

