\begin_layout Subsection
Kochen-Specker
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is one extreme case of quantum IVPMs, mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}_{\mathrm{D}}=\left\{ \imposs,\necess\right\} $
\end_inset

 is another one, corresponding to the Kochen-Specker theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochenspecker1967,peres1995quantum,Redhead1987-REDINA,Griffiths2003"

\end_inset

.
 We will use the essential idea of the Kochen-Specker theorem to prove there
 is no quantum IVPM mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}_{\mathrm{D}}=\left\{ \imposs,\necess\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Suppose there is a quantum IVPM 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset

.
 We can prove 
\begin_inset Formula $\expval{\mathbf{O}}_{\bar{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 is a singleton set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

.
 If we define the multiplication of two singleton sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda_{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{j=1}^{N}\expval{\mathbf{O}_{j}}_{\bar{\mu}}=\expval{\prod_{j=1}^{N}\mathbf{O}_{j}}_{\bar{\mu}}\label{eq:Kochen-Specker-Rules}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for any sequence of commuting observables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{O}_{j}\right\} _{j=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\expval{\cdot}_{\bar{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 satisfying these two properties, the following observables 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mermin1990Simple,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathbb{1} & \otimes\sigma_{z} & \sigma_{z} & \otimes\mathbb{1} & \sigma_{z} & \otimes\sigma_{z}\\
\sigma_{x} & \otimes\mathbb{1} & \mathbb{1} & \otimes\sigma_{x} & \sigma_{x} & \otimes\sigma_{x}\\
\sigma_{x} & \otimes\sigma_{z} & \sigma_{z} & \otimes\sigma_{x} & \sigma_{y} & \otimes\sigma_{y}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:MerminSquare}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

must have the the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1\right\} $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ -1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In each row and column, operators commutes, and each operator is the product
 of the two others, except in the third column 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma_{z}\otimes\sigma_{z}\right)\left(\sigma_{x}\otimes\sigma_{x}\right)=-\sigma_{y}\otimes\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it is clear impossible to find a IVPM 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\langle\mathbb{1} & \otimes\sigma_{z}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\sigma_{z} & \otimes\mathbb{1}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\sigma_{z} & \otimes\sigma_{z}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}}\\
\langle\sigma_{x} & \otimes\mathbb{1}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\mathbb{1} & \otimes\sigma_{x}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\sigma_{x} & \otimes\sigma_{x}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}}\\
\langle\sigma_{x} & \otimes\sigma_{z}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\sigma_{z} & \otimes\sigma_{x}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}} & \langle\sigma_{y} & \otimes\sigma_{y}\rangle_{\bar{\mu}}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:MerminSquare-values}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

satisfying Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kochen-Specker-Rules"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

